<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ziziphus obtusifolia </i>is a large shrub with robust, gray stems that end in stout thorns, forming thickets to 3 m in height. The nectar-rich flowers are inconspicuous and appear in summer after rains. Seed coats are impermeable to water, and they require scarification of the seed coat to initiate germination. Plants sprout from branches and root crowns, and growth can be rapid if moisture in available (Nellessen 2002). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ziziphus obtusifolia </i>forms occasional stands in small drainages at low elevations in the Colorado and Sonoran deserts of California. Plants here, recognized as var. <i>canescens, </i>have smaller leaves than the typical form that grows in the Chihuahua Desert. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
